\section*{Deliverable 4 (v0.1): Local Energy Inequality $\Longrightarrow$ Dyadic Carleson Candidate Bound}

\subsection*{0. Purpose}

This deliverable constructs the \emph{local} bridge plank needed for the global flux program:
a derivation of a \emph{dyadic Carleson-type dissipation bound} from the \emph{local energy inequality} for
suitable weak solutions.

The structure is:



\[
\boxed{\text{Local energy inequality}}
\ \Longrightarrow\
\boxed{\text{localized dissipation estimate}}
\ \Longrightarrow\
\boxed{\text{dyadic Carleson candidate}}
\]



with an explicit obstruction: the nonlocal pressure term and commutator interactions with cutoff functions.

This is the “local half” of Attempt Lemma~3.3 in Deliverable~3.

\subsection*{1. Setup: suitable weak solutions and local testing}

Let $u$ be a suitable weak solution to 3D incompressible Navier--Stokes on $\mathbb{T}^3$ on $[0,T]$.
Thus $u$ satisfies the local energy inequality: for every nonnegative $\phi\in C_c^\infty((0,T)\times\mathbb{T}^3)$,

\begin{align}\label{eq:lei}
\int_{\mathbb{T}^3} |u(t)|^2 \phi(t)\,dx
&+ 2\nu \int_0^t\!\!\int_{\mathbb{T}^3} |\nabla u|^2 \phi\,dx\,ds \\
&\le \int_0^t\!\!\int_{\mathbb{T}^3} |u|^2 (\partial_s\phi + \nu\Delta\phi)\,dx\,ds
+ \int_0^t\!\!\int_{\mathbb{T}^3} (|u|^2 + 2p) u\cdot\nabla\phi\,dx\,ds. \nonumber
\end{align}

We choose $\phi$ to be a \emph{parabolic cutoff} adapted to a dyadic box:


\[
\phi_{x_0,k}(s,x) = \eta\!\left(2^k|x-x_0|\right)\,\zeta\!\left(2^{2k}s\right),
\]


where $\eta,\zeta$ are smooth bump functions supported in $B(0,c)$ and $[0,1]$ respectively.

This is the standard CKN localization, but tuned to the dyadic geometry of Deliverable~3.

\subsection*{2. Localized dissipation estimate (first step)}

Testing \eqref{eq:lei} with $\phi_{x_0,k}$ yields:

\begin{align}\label{eq:lei-localized}
2\nu \int_0^{2^{-2k}}\!\!\int_{B(x_0,c2^{-k})} |\nabla u|^2\,dx\,ds
&\le
\int_0^{2^{-2k}}\!\!\int |u|^2 (\partial_s\phi_{x_0,k} + \nu\Delta\phi_{x_0,k})\,dx\,ds \\
&\quad + \int_0^{2^{-2k}}\!\!\int (|u|^2 + 2p) u\cdot\nabla\phi_{x_0,k}\,dx\,ds. \nonumber
\end{align}

The right-hand side contains three types of terms:

\begin{itemize}
  \item \textbf{Cutoff-derivative terms} involving $\partial_s\phi$ and $\Delta\phi$,
  \item \textbf{Transport-type terms} involving $|u|^2 u\cdot\nabla\phi$,
  \item \textbf{Pressure-localization terms} involving $p\,u\cdot\nabla\phi$.
\end{itemize}

The first two can be controlled by $E_0$ and local $L^3$-type bounds. The pressure term is the main obstruction.

\subsection*{3. Dyadic Carleson candidate bound (formal target)}

We aim to show that for each $(x_0,k)$,
\begin{equation}\label{eq:carleson-candidate}
2^k \int_0^{2^{-2k}}\!\!\int_{B(x_0,c2^{-k})} |\nabla u|^2\,dx\,ds
\;\le\;
C\Big( E_0 + \mathcal{F}_{\mathrm{loc}}(x_0,k) \Big),
\end{equation}
where $\mathcal{F}_{\mathrm{loc}}(x_0,k)$ is a \emph{localized flux quantity} to be matched with the shell flux
$\Pi_j$ in Deliverable~3.

This is the dyadic Carleson candidate bound that feeds Attempt Lemma~3.3.

\subsection*{4. Attempt Lemma 4.1 (Local energy inequality $\Rightarrow$ dyadic Carleson candidate)}

\paragraph{Statement.}
For each $x_0\in\mathbb{T}^3$ and $k\ge -1$, there exists a localized flux functional
$\mathcal{F}_{\mathrm{loc}}(x_0,k)$ such that
\begin{equation}\label{eq:attempt-lemma-4-1}
2^k \int_0^{2^{-2k}}\!\!\int_{B(x_0,c2^{-k})} |\nabla u|^2\,dx\,ds
\;\le\;
C\Big( E_0 + \mathcal{F}_{\mathrm{loc}}(x_0,k) \Big),
\end{equation}
where $C$ depends only on the cutoff profiles and $\nu$.

\paragraph{Sketch of derivation.}
From \eqref{eq:lei-localized}, multiply both sides by $2^k$ and estimate:

\begin{itemize}
  \item \textbf{Cutoff-derivative terms:}  
  $\partial_s\phi$ contributes a factor $2^{2k}$, $\Delta\phi$ contributes $2^{2k}$, but the support is
  $B(x_0,c2^{-k})\times[0,2^{-2k}]$, giving a net factor $2^{-k}$ after integration.  
  These terms are bounded by $C E_0$.

  \item \textbf{Transport terms:}  
  $|u|^2 u\cdot\nabla\phi$ contributes $2^k$ from $\nabla\phi$, but the support is small; using Hölder and
  interpolation, these terms are bounded by $C E_0$ or absorbed into $\mathcal{F}_{\mathrm{loc}}$.

  \item \textbf{Pressure term (main difficulty):}  
  $p\,u\cdot\nabla\phi$ requires a localized pressure decomposition:
  

\[
  p = \mathcal{R}_i\mathcal{R}_j(u_i u_j),
  \]


  where $\mathcal{R}_i$ are Riesz transforms.  
  Localizing this term introduces commutators:
  

\[
  [\mathcal{R}_i\mathcal{R}_j, \phi] (u_i u_j),
  \]


  which are nonlocal and do not have a clean sign.  
  These terms are grouped into $\mathcal{F}_{\mathrm{loc}}(x_0,k)$.
\end{itemize}

Thus \eqref{eq:attempt-lemma-4-1} holds with


\[
\mathcal{F}_{\mathrm{loc}}(x_0,k)
:= \int_0^{2^{-2k}}\!\!\int_{B(x_0,c2^{-k})} 
\big( |u|^2 u\cdot\nabla\phi + 2p\,u\cdot\nabla\phi \big)\,dx\,ds.
\]



\subsection*{5. Obstruction (explicit)}

The obstruction to upgrading \eqref{eq:attempt-lemma-4-1} to the global dyadic Carleson bound of Deliverable~3 is:

\begin{itemize}
  \item \textbf{Pressure nonlocality:}  
  The commutator $[\mathcal{R}_i\mathcal{R}_j, \phi]$ is nonlocal and does not admit a clean dyadic summation
  without additional structure.

  \item \textbf{Localization-commutator interaction:}  
  The cutoff $\phi_{x_0,k}$ introduces $2^k$-scaled gradients that interact with high-frequency components of $u$,
  producing borderline terms.

  \item \textbf{No unconditional parabolic-box control:}  
  The local energy inequality controls $\int |\nabla u|^2$ on each box, but does not prevent concentration across
  infinitely many boxes at different scales.
\end{itemize}

These obstructions are exactly the ones identified in Attempt Lemma~3.3.

